{"abstract": "The selling of a movie with blockbuster potential is big business, much of it online, as marketing for \u201cThe Hunger Games\u201d has shown.", "web_url": "https://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/03/19/the-breakfast-meeting-feeding-hunger-games-fans-and-the-theater-of-journalism/", "snippet": "The selling of a movie with blockbuster potential is big business, much of it online, as marketing for \u201cThe Hunger Games\u201d has shown.", "lead_paragraph": "The marketing effort behind the movie \u201cThe Hunger Games\u201d has been a marriage of traditional methods \u2014 billboards, magazine covers \u2014 and social-media promotions guided by Lionsgate\u2019s marketing division, Brooks Barnes writes. No doubt the film, which opens on Friday, had a built-in advantage because of the many young fans of the book series. Even so, feeding the flame online has been a preoccupation for a year for Lionsgate, with a strategy that included hooking in the blogs, a series of well-timed contests at Twitter and Facebook, a YouTube channel, a Tumblr blog, etc.", "source": "The New York Times", "multimedia": [], "headline": {"main": "The Breakfast Meeting: Feeding \u2018Hunger Games\u2019 Fans, and the Theater of Journalism", "kicker": "Media Decoder", "content_kicker": null, "print_headline": "", "name": null, "seo": null, "sub": null}, "keywords": [{"name": "subject", "value": "Amazon Kindle", "rank": 1, "major": "N"}, {"name": "subject", "value": "Books and Literature", "rank": 2, "major": "N"}, {"name": "subject", "value": "Movies", "rank": 3, "major": "N"}, {"name": "subject", "value": "Television", "rank": 4, "major": "N"}, {"name": "subject", "value": "Writing and Writers", "rank": 5, "major": "N"}, {"name": "persons", "value": "Barnes, Brooks", "rank": 6, "major": "N"}, {"name": "persons", "value": "Carr, David", "rank": 7, "major": "N"}, {"name": "persons", "value": "Collins, Suzanne", "rank": 8, "major": "N"}, {"name": "persons", "value": "Daisey, Mike", "